@@eThe Delta City: Kowloon@@N

@@yKowloon@@N rises on terraced stone where the Jhen River empties into
Coppersalt Bay. Before the walls, the delta was called the @@dShallow
Thousand@@N -- a drowned lacework of stilts, prayer poles, and contraband
docks. Its oldest inhabitants were the @@eLampkeepers@@N, solitary hermits
who maintained oil beacons so night fishermen could navigate the shifting
channels. They gave the delta its poetic name: the @@yField of Lanterns@@N.

Then came the @@rAshfall Monsoon@@N. Three years of black volcanic rain from
the Cinderteeth Mountains choked canals, collapsed roofs, and turned fresh
water bitter with sulfur. The third year was the worst: the village of
Yen-Mak drowned whole -- six hundred souls lost in a single night. The
survivors lit signal fires on a basalt outcrop and waited. Rescue came
from every direction: former enemies pulling the same ropes.

In the fourth year, six surviving houses convened on that outcrop and
forged the @@yNeon Covenant@@N -- inked in phosphorescent squid dye that
glowed under torchlight, proving it had not been altered in darkness.

@@eThe Five Seats of Rule@@N govern modern Kowloon:
@@lHarbor Syndics@@N regulate docks, tariffs, and foreign vessel licensing.
@@gJade Magistracy@@N holds tax authority, civil law, and emergency rationing.
@@WTemple Circle@@N maintains healing houses, funerary rites, and sanctuary law.
@@dWardens of Iron@@N command walls, gate discipline, and city militia.
@@eCourier Lantern Office@@N operates the registry, census, and signal network.

@@yColors of Power@@N are civic shorthand, readable at a glance:
@@rCrimson@@N marks emergency lanes and execution authority.
@@gJade@@N marks permits, granaries, and magistrate offices.
@@yGold@@N marks licensed merchants and bonded craftsmen.
@@lBlue@@N marks pumps, sluices, and harbor jurisdiction.
@@dViolet@@N marks licensed night markets and sanctioned ambiguity.
@@eCyan@@N marks floodline indicators and courier relay stations.

Beneath the central square, rumor persists of the @@rBlack Ledger@@N -- the
unredacted census of the six founding houses, sealed in a flooded cistern.
If it exists, it could expose forged lineages, oaths signed under duress,
and names of those transferred to the Spirebound Conclave. Every faction
in Kowloon would kill to find it, or to ensure it stays buried.

The city's four gates each bear a name: the @@gJade Gate@@N north toward
highland trade routes, the @@dIron Gate@@N south toward the wetland frontier,
the @@yLantern Gate@@N west toward pilgrim paths hung with oil lanterns by
those who made it home, and the @@lTide Gate@@N east toward harbor and open sea.

Each autumn, the city observes the @@dAshfall Vigil@@N. All lights are
extinguished for one hour at midnight. When they return, the Executioner
strikes the covenant stone three times: once for the dead, once for the
living, once for those not yet born.
